AIPCK Archbishop John Mugecha died on Monday night at Outspan Hospital on the outskirts of Nyeri town.The 72-year old had been sick for about a year. He left behind a widow and six children.Tetu leaders, led by deputy commissioner Herman Shambi, flocked Mugecha's Ithe Kahuno home on Tuesday.Parliamentary aspirant Peter Kamuthu, eulogised him as a nationalist who loved his community.&ldquo;He loved to fight for marginalised people in the community, especially in Tetu. He would speak his mind and was very generous, kind and courageous,&rdquo; he said.Read: Kiambu clergy tells Uhuru to snub ICCNyeri woman representative aspirant Rahab Mukami said Mugecha was a fearless man of God who was devoted to his work.The Archbishop had been leading the church for more than 30 years after it split from the African Independent Pentecostal Church of Africa. It was headed at the time by Benjamin Kahihia, now deceased.The vocal and outspoken cleric, who hails from Tetu constituency in Nyeri county, opened many churches around the country. Mugecha once criticised State House Chief of Staff Joseph Kinyua for not ensuring the roads to his mother's home were in good condition.He issued the remarks while presiding over the burial of Kinyua's mother Hannah Wanjiru.But President Uhuru Kenyatta defended Kinyua, saying the work he has done for Kenyans is impressive. He added that the Archbishop should have consulted the President instead of the Chief of Staff.